  <article class="prose mx-auto mt-8 max-w-3xl">
    <h1>Apache Iceberg Schema Evolution and Hidden Partitioning</h1>

    <p>
      Two of Iceberg's most practically valuable features are schema evolution
      without data rewrites and partition schemes that are invisible to query
      authors. Both come from the same core design choice: Iceberg tracks
      columns by numeric ID rather than by name, and it tracks partition values
      in metadata rather than in file paths.
    </p>

    <h2>Schema Evolution: How Column IDs Work</h2>

    <Mermaid
      class="my-8"
      diagram={`graph TD
    subgraph SCHEMA["Table Schema in metadata.json"]
        C1["Field ID 1: order_id (BIGINT)"]
        C2["Field ID 2: cust_id (BIGINT) — renamed from customer_id"]
        C3["Field ID 3: total (DOUBLE)"]
        C4["Field ID 4: region (STRING) — added later"]
        C5["Field ID 5: status (STRING)"]
    end
    subgraph FILE1["data-00001.parquet (written before rename + add)"]
        F1["field_id=1: order values"]
        F2["field_id=2: customer values"]
        F3["field_id=3: total values"]
        F5["field_id=5: status values"]
        NOTE["field_id=4 missing — reader returns NULL"]
    end
    SCHEMA --> FILE1`}
    />

    <table>
      <thead
        ><tr
          ><th>Operation</th><th>Data files rewritten?</th><th>What happens</th
          ></tr
        ></thead
      >
      <tbody>
        <tr
          ><td>Add column</td><td>No</td><td
            >Old files return NULL for the new column. New files include the new
            field.</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Rename column</td><td>No</td><td
            >Schema metadata updates the name. Parquet files store by field ID,
            so data is unchanged.</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Reorder columns</td><td>No</td><td
            >Column order is metadata-only. Physical storage is by field ID.</td
          ></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td>Drop column</td><td>No</td><td
            >The field ID is retired. Old data files still contain the bytes,
            but readers skip them.</td
          ></tr
        >
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <pre><code>-- Add a column with a default value
ALTER TABLE analytics.orders ADD COLUMN channel STRING DEFAULT 'web';

-- Rename a column
ALTER TABLE analytics.orders RENAME COLUMN cust_id TO customer_id;

-- Drop a column
ALTER TABLE analytics.orders DROP COLUMN legacy_field;</code></pre>

    <h2>Hidden Partitioning</h2>
    <p>
      In Hive, users must include the partition column in every query to get
      partition pruning. Iceberg handles this automatically. You declare a
      partition transform on an existing data column, Iceberg derives the
      partition value at write time and stores it in manifest metadata. Query
      authors write filters on the real data column and Iceberg applies
      partition pruning automatically.
    </p>

    <Mermaid
      class="my-8"
      diagram={`graph LR
    subgraph USER["What the user writes"]
        Q["SELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_date >= '2026-05-01'"]
    end
    subgraph ICEBERG["What Iceberg does internally"]
        PRUNE["Evaluate manifest partition summaries: only open manifests where max(months(order_date)) >= 2026-05"]
        SKIP["Skip manifests and files outside the range"]
        READ["Read only matching files"]
    end
    USER --> ICEBERG`}
    />

    <h3>Partition Transforms</h3>

    <table>
      <thead
        ><tr
          ><th>Transform</th><th>Example</th><th>Derived partition value</th
          ></tr
        ></thead
      >
      <tbody>
        <tr
          ><td><code>identity(col)</code></td><td
            ><code>identity(region)</code></td
          ><td>The raw value of region</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td><code>year(col)</code></td><td><code>year(order_date)</code></td
          ><td>2026, 2025, ...</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td><code>month(col)</code></td><td
            ><code>month(order_date)</code></td
          ><td>2026-05, 2026-04, ...</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td><code>day(col)</code></td><td><code>day(order_date)</code></td
          ><td>2026-05-15, ...</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td><code>hour(col)</code></td><td><code>hour(event_ts)</code></td
          ><td>2026-05-15-10, ...</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td><code>bucket(col, N)</code></td><td
            ><code>bucket(customer_id, 16)</code></td
          ><td>0 through 15 (hash buckets)</td></tr
        >
        <tr
          ><td><code>truncate(col, W)</code></td><td
            ><code>truncate(zip_code, 3)</code></td
          ><td>First 3 characters</td></tr
        >
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>Partition Evolution</h2>
    <p>
      Because partition values are in metadata rather than data files, you can
      change a table's partition scheme without rewriting existing data. Old
      files keep their old partition layout. New files use the new layout. The
      query planner handles both.
    </p>

    <pre><code>-- Switch from monthly to daily partitioning
ALTER TABLE analytics.orders
  REPLACE PARTITION FIELD months(order_date)
  WITH days(order_date);

-- Add a second partition dimension
ALTER TABLE analytics.orders
  ADD PARTITION FIELD identity(region);</code></pre>

    <Mermaid
      class="my-8"
      diagram={`graph TD
    A["Old files: partitioned by months(order_date), manifest records spec_id=0"]
    B["New files: partitioned by days(order_date), manifest records spec_id=1"]
    C["Query planner: reads both manifest sets, applies correct pruning for each spec_id"]
    A --> C
    B --> C`}
    />

